    <title>‘Nvidia controlling Arm could create real problems,’ UK regulator concludes</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0V-y4GgPsoBKmJh90KrCo2uQTyM=/0x1:2000x1334/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/69754619/NVIDIA_Endeavor_building_logo.0.jpg" /&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="390JrG"&gt;Remember when Nvidia’s CEO warned yesterday that &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/19/22632017/nvidia-acquisition-arm-timeframe-18-months-schedule-regulatory-scrutiny"&gt;buying Arm might take “longer than initially thought&lt;/a&gt;,” but that it was no big deal and “not one particular delay”? It sure &lt;em&gt;sounds&lt;/em&gt; like a big deal as of today: on Friday, the UK’s Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) has recommended a Phase 2 investigation, because it’s worried that Nvidia would be incentivized to stifle innovation. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="kwUmEZ"&gt;“We’re concerned that NVIDIA controlling Arm could create real problems for NVIDIA’s rivals by limiting their access to key technologies, and ultimately stifling innovation across a number of important and growing markets. This could end up with consumers missing out on new products, or prices going up,” writes CMA chief executive Andrea Coscelli, &lt;a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cma-finds-competition-concerns-with-nvidia-s-purchase-of-arm"&gt;in a press...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
